DESCRIPTION: Used when referring to someone or something for the first time in a text or conversation.
Put in (an additional element, ingredient, etc.).
To put into operation or effect
A flat stiff usually small and rectangular piece of material (such as paper, cardboard, or plastic) usually bearing information.
A thing made to be similar or identical to another.
Physical harm caused to something in such a way as to impair its value, usefulness, or normal function.
Get rid of (someone or something) as no longer useful or desirable.
Being the same in quantity, size, degree, or value.
Obtain or secure (something desired, favorable, or profitable).
Expressing movement or action with the result that someone or something becomes enclosed or surrounded by something else.
Indicating an association between two entities, typically one of belonging.
A heap of things laid or lying one on top of another.
Referring to a specific thing or situation just mentioned.
Identifying the person or thing affected.
Belonging to or associated with the person or people that the speaker is addressing.
